{"info": {"author": "Benjamin Johnson", "author_email": "bmjcode@gmail.com", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 4 - Beta", "License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Operating System :: OS Independent", "Programming Language :: Python :: 2", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3"], "description": "**mailcomposer** aims to provide a simple, cross-platform interface for composing emails through an external application like Microsoft Outlook. Some reasons you might use it are:\n\n* You're behind a corporate firewall, and are only able to send email using Outlook.\n* You don't have an SMTP server, or don't want the hassle of using `smtplib`.\n* You just prefer your desktop email client.\n\nHere's how easy it is to use:\n\n```python\n# This automatically selects an appropriate email application\nfrom mailcomposer import MailComposer\nmc = MailComposer()\n\n# Set some message headers\nmc.to = \"nobody@example.com\"\nmc.subject = \"Testing mailcomposer\"\n\n# Set the message body\nmc.body = \"This is a demonstration of the mailcomposer package.\"\n\n# Attach this README file\nmc.attach_file(\"README.md\")\n\n# Display the message in your email application\nmc.display()\n```\n\nThe mailcomposer module can also be called as a script from the command line. When used this way, it provides an interface similar to the Unix `mail` utility. For more information, try `python -m mailcomposer --help`.\n\n\n## Features\n\nNotable features include:\n\n* Straightforward API\n* Cross-platform\n* Runs on both Python 2 and 3\n* Uses your desktop email client; no SMTP server required\n* To, CC, and BCC fields accept single recipients or Python lists\n* Messages can be composed in either plain-text or HTML format\n* Attachments are easy -- just pass the filename\n\n\n## Supported Email Applications\n\nSupported email applications currently include:\n\n* Microsoft Outlook (Windows only; requires [pywin32](https://pypi.org/project/pywin32/))\n* Mozilla Thunderbird\n\nOn Unix systems, mailcomposer can also access other email applications via the `xdg-email` utility from [xdg-utils](https://freedesktop.org/wiki/Software/xdg-utils/). However, some features like setting the body format are not supported using `xdg-email`.\n\n\n", "description_content_type": "text/markdown", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "https://github.com/bmjcode/mailcomposer", "keywords": "", "license": "", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "mailcomposer", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/mailcomposer/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/mailcomposer/", "project_urls": {"Homepage": "https://github.com/bmjcode/mailcomposer"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/mailcomposer/0.2.4/", "requires_dist": null, "requires_python": "", "summary": "API for composing emails through an external application", "version": "0.2.4", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <p><strong>mailcomposer</strong> aims to provide a simple, cross-platform interface for composing emails through an external application like Microsoft Outlook. Some reasons you might use it are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>You're behind a corporate firewall, and are only able to send email using Outlook.</li>\n<li>You don't have an SMTP server, or don't want the hassle of using <code>smtplib</code>.</li>\n<li>You just prefer your desktop email client.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Here's how easy it is to use:</p>\n<pre><span class=\"c1\"># This automatically selects an appropriate email application</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">from</span> <span class=\"nn\">mailcomposer</span> <span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">MailComposer</span>\n<span class=\"n\">mc</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">MailComposer</span><span class=\"p\">()</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\"># Set some message headers</span>\n<span class=\"n\">mc</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">to</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s2\">\"nobody@example.com\"</span>\n<span class=\"n\">mc</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">subject</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s2\">\"Testing mailcomposer\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\"># Set the message body</span>\n<span class=\"n\">mc</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">body</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"s2\">\"This is a demonstration of the mailcomposer package.\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\"># Attach this README file</span>\n<span class=\"n\">mc</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">attach_file</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"s2\">\"README.md\"</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\"># Display the message in your email application</span>\n<span class=\"n\">mc</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"n\">display</span><span class=\"p\">()</span>\n</pre>\n<p>The mailcomposer module can also be called as a script from the command line. When used this way, it provides an interface similar to the Unix <code>mail</code> utility. For more information, try <code>python -m mailcomposer --help</code>.</p>\n<h2>Features</h2>\n<p>Notable features include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Straightforward API</li>\n<li>Cross-platform</li>\n<li>Runs on both Python 2 and 3</li>\n<li>Uses your desktop email client; no SMTP server required</li>\n<li>To, CC, and BCC fields accept single recipients or Python lists</li>\n<li>Messages can be composed in either plain-text or HTML format</li>\n<li>Attachments are easy -- just pass the filename</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Supported Email Applications</h2>\n<p>Supported email applications currently include:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Microsoft Outlook (Windows only; requires <a href=\"https://pypi.org/project/pywin32/\" rel=\"nofollow\">pywin32</a>)</li>\n<li>Mozilla Thunderbird</li>\n</ul>\n<p>On Unix systems, mailcomposer can also access other email applications via the <code>xdg-email</code> utility from <a href=\"https://freedesktop.org/wiki/Software/xdg-utils/\" rel=\"nofollow\">xdg-utils</a>. However, some features like setting the body format are not supported using <code>xdg-email</code>.</p>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 5797336, "releases": {"0.1.0": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "f7cec3467b8f4e67631e8e5cade0fcf3", "sha256": "0e0d6ca7cb024899fdaa16fe4cc3b44e204caced524ddc3f190d77c6093f9e97"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "mailcomposer-0.1.0-py2.py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "f7cec3467b8f4e67631e8e5cade0fcf3", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py2.py3", "requires_python": null, "size": 9900, "upload_time": "2018-09-03T23:56:34", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2018-09-03T23:56:34.716250Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/23/72/8138b93dc270caef724f99412051d953361c498fd7258f096b8199e3a9da/mailcomposer-0.1.0-py2.py3-none-any.whl", "yanked": false}, {"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "0e0cbf132b81fc44545374442fc62f12", "sha256": "b905f7027d5350ab4ff53c1545cc139e233cc16fcd9e263434c5ca9aaf5fd61e"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "mailcomposer-0.1.0.tar.gz", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "0e0cbf132b81fc44545374442fc62f12", "packagetype": "sdist", "python_version": "source", "requires_python": null, "size": 6038, "upload_time": "2018-09-03T23:56:35", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2018-09-03T23:56:35.928278Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/37/98/d92ba7be6e33be66bb6771b1ea8d5d882ca623d3007babe93ef14947a635/mailcomposer-0.1.0.tar.gz", "yanked": false}], "0.2.0": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "63d5bf653f66126743f1a63dbbe573a4", "sha256": "de9d1886941015e6f93c5fea19353c501a0abfe8caa7cd9bdac863c1ba70fe72"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "mailcomposer-0.2.0-py2.py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "63d5bf653f66126743f1a63dbbe573a4", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py2.py3", "requires_python": null, "size": 12896, "upload_time":